title: For Sale:  Rem 700 Custom 220 Swift
postcontent: I am selling this rifle (and two others) for a friend. He had it built and has used it extensively in the prairie dog fields. He generally only buys the "good stuff" and this rifle is no exception.Action appears to be tuned (not sure if "blueprinted" is appropriate term) and is silky smooth. The serial number is A6392XXX making it late-80s according to my research. Glued-in single shot follower. I see no manufacturer markings on the trigger. The trigger shoe is wide and serrated. Trigger breaks at 2-1/2#. Barrel is stainless and fluted with muzzle break. Overall length is 28" from brake to bolt. Diameter is 1.23" at recoil lug and .90" at brake. Exterior shows signs of use, but could be cleaned up nicely with a fresh bead-blasting. This barrel is "well-seasoned" in that to my untrained eye, it appears the rifling is well-worn for the first 8-10". I have no idea if this barrel has any accuracy left or if it can be set back.Stock is fiberglass and of unknown manufacture. The forend is 2-3/8" wide with rounded bottom. There is one 3/4" x 1/4" piece of the surface coat missing on left side of forend where you can see the mesh beneath. It would be an easy repair during re-painting. The bedding is well done, obviously by a professional.Overall, a nice rifle with potential to become a VERY nice rifle with a little TLC and perhaps a new barrel. More photos at: http://s698.photobucket.com/user/cjkostic/library/Remington 700 220 Swift?sort=3&page=1

title: For Sale/Trade:  Egyptian Hakim w/bayonet
postcontent: All matching numbers. Clean rifle. This rifle will make a collector happy. Hakim rifles have Arabic script on them and were used in Middle Eastern Wars. They also shoot 8mm Mauser, which you can still find as surplus. This Hakim comes with a bayonet and scabbard both marked in Arabic. The Hakim (pronounced HA-KEEM) was the first rifle ever produced by Egypt. It was the result of a modernization effort after their very significant defeat to the new state of Israel, in 1949. Some time prior to 1955, Egypt purchased the machinery and with the help of Swedish engineers set up the tooling originally designed to produce the Swedish Ljungman AG42 Rifle. The factory was set up in Egypt and the original AG42 was adapted to fulfill the needs of the Egyptians. The caliber of the rifle was changed from 6.5x55mm to 7.97 (8mm) Mauser, reportedly due to the large amounts of 8mm Mauser ammunition left over from WWII in the country at the time. The Hakim served in the second Arab-Israeli war in 1956 and the third Arab-Israeli war (also known as the “six day war”) in 1967. Only est.71,000 were prouduced.All matching numbers. The bore on this is beautiful. The wood is sound and in very Good shape. Fired 10 rounds with perfect function. Gas system works properly and is adjustable. Tightest example I've ever handled. The bayonet is in just as good condition. The streaks in the picture are cosmoline not scratches. Price is Firm. May consider certain trades. If you have any questions please ask. Must have valid OH DL, be of age, and initial BOS. Here is a little more info. Thanks for looking. Comes with bayonet and scabbard.

title: For Sale:  CVA 50 Cal. Muzzle Loader
postcontent:
I have is  a Connecticut Valley Arms “Hawkins” style, Frontier Carbine in .50 caliber. This rifle has a blued octagonal barrel with a wood stock & brass hardware with QD swivel studs front and back.  
 
This was the first Black powder Rifle I ever had, I got the rifle from a buddy and I Thought he was giving me a deal. When I got home I discovered that the sights were missing  ($40.00 from factory). The ram rod was also missing, I got a fiberglass one with brass ends at Walmart for $25.00. 
 
This rifle does have a couple of scratches and a place where the finish is pealing on the stock, it probably needs refinishing, but I was going to wait until I got the rifle shooting like I wanted before I did this. Due to heart surgery things have just not worked out like I wanted.
Before I became disabled and was working every day, a couple of people I shot with had muzzle loaders, one of them used loose powder, which I thought was a mess. The other used something called “ Pyrodex Pellets”, this was 50 grains of smokeless Black powder pressed into a pellet. These things did not spill powder everywhere, and 2 pellets equal 100 grains of black powder. I liked these and bought a box of 100, there are several other pellets that came with some bullets. 

I don't think I shot the rifle over 3 or 4 times! I got sick before I could really even get the new sights dialed in. 
Of course I bought bullets also, here again I went with less mess, I bought bullets and sabots, instead of lube and wading.
Two powder pellets, a bullet and sabot, ram it home, no mess no fuss, cap it an your ready to fire...

There is a new unopened pack of powder belt bullets, these have a plastic tip to help the bullet expand, I beleave these are 200 grain.
 
 
There are also ten 300 grain hollow point bullets.
 
I got these because my wife's uncle has seen Elk on his farm, and I was hoping to get an Elk tag... There are eleven other bullets & sabots which I think are 250 grain, copper jacketed lead HP bullets.
 
The next problem I discovered was that the rifle would not shoot!Turned out the old #10 nipple was not hot enough to ignite the pellets, So I replaced it with a new, bigger #11 nipple.
 
These came in a package of three and there are two #11 nipples still new in pack along with a new tin of the hotter #11 Percussion caps, several caps are missing. 
 
There are several other accessories include with the rifle,there is a Thompson Center 50 cal black powder cleaning kit. 
 
There is also a real horn, I've never made it a functional powder horn because I used the pellets. I did install ends on it and it looks great hanging beside the rifle when not in use.
 
I had this big idea that I would make a set of buckskins after I got a couple of deer hides. So I got a cheap knife from knife from Smokey Mount Knife Works, this knife has plastic handles and a fake Damascus blade. Along with the buckskins, I was going to replace the handles with deer horn and make a sheath from deer hide. it's still new in the box.
 
After I collected all these items I needed some place to keep it, so I got a Allen company “made in the U.S.A” soft case for a scoped rifle.

title: For Sale:  Complete Alice Pack for sale
postcontent:
I have one complete Alice pack for sale! 
 
FRAME: The frame was just a standard issue USGI Alice pack frame, complete with a soldiers name and old dried Duct tape residue. (I found this frame on the the web, it fairly close to what mine looked like). I tried several cleaners and wound up spraying and scraping to get it all off, and of course most of the paint came off also. 
 
I had several can of flat camo paint, and came across a can of Army Green, so I sprayed the frame with that. This turned out to be a big mistake, because I did this at night. Next morning
I discovered it was a bright, flat celery color! I got something called “Deep Forest Green” (this was the closest Wally World had to OD), and resprayed the frame with about 3 light coats of that. The paint is darker than the pictures show, but it's real close to original color. Frame has total of about 6 coats of paint.
 
HANDLE:  I had 13 1/2 ft. of some old OD nylon rope, don't know if it was military or not! I cut this into sections, and used four, 32 inch long pieces to weave into a handle for the 
frame. After handle was double tied, I put several drops Gorilla Glue on the knots, then after the glue dried I cut off the excess rope and seared the ends with a match. 
 
 
MEDINUM ALICE PACK: "All-purpose Lightweight Individual Carrying Equipment". While this pack is in good shape, it does have some wear. It has the Maim compartment, with radio pouch in the back. Map pouch in top flap, three pockets on the out side, plus, Two Inch Nylon Webbing sewn Around the Top of the Bag and on Both Sides to Attach Additional Gear / pouches on the Outside of the Pack.
 
GOOD: The Nylon On The flap is not peeling away as happens with most of these packs. 
 
BAD: The support pocket that slips over the Alice frame shows some wear. One of the Metal Drain Vent Holes at the Bottom of the pack is loose! And on the the left top side between the webbing, there is a hole that has been repaired... 
 
MOLLE II SHOULDER STRAPS COMPLEET: with sternum strap: in Woodland Camo. These straps have a Large back panel and 2" wide support strap, with a D-Ring on each strap, with thick mold-and-mildew-resistant padding. They also have the sternum strap. Originally; the lower Quick-Release Buckles were missing, I bought a new set that look like what the Marines call “Foliage”, which is a greenish / grayish color. 
 
MOLLE II KIDNEY PAD: in Woodland Camo. This kidney pad has durable thick padding to make the load more comfortable on the lower back. These can be used with the MOLLE frame or as an upgrade to the ALICE pack frame, and is adaptable to other back pack frames, I've even seen them on tree stands.. This is military surplus and has been used, there are a couple of wear spots on the inside top.

title: For Sale:  TWIN PAIR COLT 38 Super POLISHED NICKEL + GOLD         .38 SUPER COLT CONSECUTIVE #'s DELUXE PAIR *WoW!
postcontent:
Here is a very hard to find matched consecutively numbered pair of Colt full size Government model 38 Supers in a polished bright nickel and gold set. Serial numbers 2930424 and 2930425.
These Colt Government Models are completely finished in bright Nickel with 24K gold trim. Each one of these deluxe Colts comes with two magazines. Each body, foot, and follower are high polished bright nickel.
This pair is new and un-fired. The mainspring housings were plastic from the factory but we fixed that! Before being polished and 2X plated in 24 karat gold, we replaced the plastic housing parts (backstraps) with steel housings.
The standard plain black factory aluminum triggers were precision drilled with three holes then nickel then gold finished as an additional custom feature.
We have taken every precaution and all the steps necessary to be sure this consecutive numbered pair of Colt .38 supers are worthy of a place in any top shelf collection.
Both of these Colts were disassembled, then all parts were individually worked and hand polished. Each of the large and small parts, pins, and screws were given attention. Once each part was hand polished to a bright finish, every part of these Colts were bright nickel plated.
The small parts and pins were then 2X plated in 24 karat gold that was applied in a process ensuring even color and distribution. The end result is a fine pair of Colt .38 supers that have been worked into a rare consecutive numbered set that would be very hard to find elsewhere.
This consecutive set represents our best work. Attention to detail is our specialty and we have focused all of our best efforts here on this pair of .38 Super Colts. We are careful to leave the corners, edges, and markings sharp. The nickel finish is both beautiful and durable. You could save these and hand them down to future generations, or you could shoot a box of shells up every night keeping the coyotes away.
We installed hand picked pairs of white pearlite grips with matching large Colt gold icons, but other grips styles are available
